  "doc_id": "32725",
  "text": "One potential strategy to promote axonal regeneration after SCI consists in creating a microenvironment enriched of neurotrophic factors which favor MSCs survival and differentiation. MSCs can be genetically manipulated to overexpress neurotrophic factors, such as BDNF, NT-3 and the neurotrophin-3 receptor (TrkC) and GDNF [CITATION_1] or alternatively the expression of deleterious proteins can be suppressed by gene silencing. BMSCs overexpressing BDNF were encapsulated in alginate-based anisotropic capillary hydrogels and grafted into the lesion of hemisected rat spinal cord [CITATION_2] . Interestingly, these alginate scaffolds conjugated with BMSCs overexpressing BDNF showed an enhanced ability to induce axonal regeneration four weeks after implantation, as proved by the reduced cavity formation, compared to the control group which received scaffold plus BMSCs expressing only the Green Fluorescent Protein (GFP) [CITATION_3] .",
